Technical Troubleshooting & Design Iterations
1. NAT Mapping Behavior & Simulation Constraints
Scenario: Implementing NAT Overload (PAT) on the HQ Router to support multiple internal interfaces.

Action: Attempted to bind the NAT process to multiple internal interfaces using a single Access Control List (ACL).

Observed Behavior: The environment did not maintain the persistence of the first mapping once a second ip nat inside source command was applied. The router appeared to overwrite the configuration with the most recent command.

Attempted Workaround: Created duplicate ACLs to isolate the traffic for each interface and applied separate NAT statements. This also did not achieve the desired concurrent translation.

Technical Conclusion: Based on these observations, the current simulation environment (Packet Tracer) demonstrated inconsistent handling of multi-interface NAT-to-ACL bindings. To maintain the integrity of the enterprise design, I have left the configuration in its intended state.

Next Step: Validation of this specific NAT logic is a primary objective for the upcoming migration to the EVE-NG platform.

2. Major Architectural Pivot: Access & Server Farm Redundancy
Scenario: Conflict between Layer 2 Security and Link Aggregation.

The Challenge: Identified a critical conflict between LACP (Link Aggregation) and DHCP Snooping within the simulation. The environment struggled to maintain the trust state on Port-Channel interfaces, compromising DHCP stability.

The Solution: I performed a strategic redesign of the Access Layer:

Decoupled LACP from Access Ports: Transitioned Server Farm and End-User switches to a stable, single-link configuration with optimized Spanning Tree (PVST+) convergence.

Focused Aggregation on Distribution: Kept EtherChannel strictly between Distribution multilayer switches for maximum backbone throughput.

Result: This change ensured 100% stability of the DHCP Snooping and DAI databases while maintaining a high-availability core.
